            <biogHist>
                <p>Donald MacCormick was the son of Alexander MacCormick and Sarah née MacMillan. He
                    is recorded in 1881 as living in the house of their brother John (born c. 1829)
                    in Cille Pheadair, together with their sister Mary (born c. 1831), brother Angus
                    (born c. 1844), and cousin Mary. Ten and twenty years later the household
                    remained the same, although Mary had left. Donald and his younger brother Angus
                    are recorded in the censuses as speaking English as well as Gaelic, a relatively
                    unusual skill suggesting they may have spent time outwith the Gàidhealtachd.
                    Staying with them as a visitor in 1901 is Flora Gillies, a former dairymaid born
                    in Morar. Donald MacCormick died in June 1916 of senile decay and his brother
                    Angus was witness to his death. MacCormick’s age was given as 80, apparently
                    nearly twenty years older than he actually was.</p>
                <p>Donald MacCormick is given as the source for a version of the peat-smooring
                    prayer <span>Smàladh an Teine</span>, and for a version of the prayer before
                    sleep, <span>Altachadh Leapa</span> (‘Tha mise cur m’ anama ’s mo chuirp…). If
                    the later ascription of the following items to ‘Don[ald] Macdonald, crofter
                    Grimnis, Benbecula’ is mistaken – the original ascriptions read ‘From the same,
                    same time’ – he may have supplied considerably more: the genealogical prayer to
                    St Bride <span>Sloinneadh Brìde</span>; another <span>Altachadh Leapa</span>
                    (‘Laidhidh mise noc[hd]’); the churning charm <span>Rann Maistridh</span> (‘Thig
                    a chuinneag thig’); the fairy song <span>A Mhòr a Mhòr, till ri d’
                    mhacan</span>; a humorous song or poem <span>Tochra na Mnatha</span>; the
                    milking song <span>Hi u oilegan i u o m aighean</span>; names of plants
                    connected with charming; <span>Eolas a Bhun Deirg</span>, the red water charm; a
                    charm against leprosy; various plant cures; and a fairy story concerning a girl
                    trapped in a <span>brùgh</span> [CW87/54-65].</p>
                <p>It should, however, be noted that the <span>Sloinneadh</span> or
                        <span>Sloinntireachd Brìde</span> – and therefore all items which follow –
                    is definitely ascribed to Donald MacDonald in [CW359 fos.36–7], and in its
                    eventual publication in <span localType="mods-titleinfo">CG</span> i, 174–5 [cf.
                    ibid., 375; John Gregorson Campbell (ed. Ronald Black), <span
                        localType="mods-titleinfo">The Gaelic Otherworld</span> (Edinburgh, 2005),
                    675]. The date given for the interview with MacCormick, 21 December 1885, and
                    the fact that these items are written into a transcription notebook, suggest
                    that the recorder was not Alexander Carmichael himself, but probably his
                    assistant John Ewen MacRury (1853–1909). A heavily edited and polished version
                    of Donald MacCormick’s <span>Altachadh Leapa</span> was published in <span
                        localType="mods-titleinfo">Carmina Gadelica</span> as <span>Urnuigh
                        Chadail</span> [<span localType="mods-titleinfo">CG</span> i, 72–3].</p>
